title: SFH visits Central and Western District (with photos)
content_text:
p>
	The Secretary for Food and Health, Dr Ko Wing-man, visited Central and 
	Western District this afternoon (February 28) to see for himself the 
	fixed-pitch hawker stall facilities and dental care services in the 
	district, and to exchange views with District Councillors on matters under 
	the purview of the Food and Health Bureau. Accompanied by the District Officer (Wan Chai), Miss Cheryl Chow, and the 
	Chairman of the Central and Western District Council, Mr Yip Wing-shing, Dr

Ko first inspected the fixed-pitch hawker areas on Li Yuen Street East and 
	Li Yuen Street West to learn more about the implementation progress of the 
	Assistance Scheme for Hawkers in Fixed-pitch Hawker Areas under the Food and 
	Environmental Hygiene Department. Noting that the assistance scheme aims to 
	reduce the fire risk and improve the fire safety standards of hawker stalls, 
	Dr Ko said he understood that some hawkers at these two fixed-pitch hawker

areas needed to reconstruct or relocate their stalls due to concerns about 
	fire safety. Dr Ko expressed his gratitude to the hawkers for their 
	co-operation so that the scheme could be rolled out smoothly. Dr Ko then visited the Tung Wah Group of Hospitals Community Dental Clinic 
	in Sheung Wan, the first community dental clinic outside a hospital setting 
	that provides comprehensive dental treatment and oral health-care services. 
	The clinic has also set up an outreach dental service team to provide free 
	basic dental and oral health-care services to elderly people residing in the

basic dental and oral health-care services to elderly people residing in the designated residential care homes or receiving services in the designated day care centres in the district. The outreach dental service team provided services for more than 3 200 senior citizens in the district from April 2013 to January 2014.
　　
Before concluding his visit, Dr Ko met with Central and Western District Councillors to listen to their concerns and suggestions on medical and

Councillors to listen to their concerns and suggestions on medical and environmental hygiene issues in the district. Ends/Friday, February 28, 2014
